            h2: "Urban and Transport Emissions: Traffic congestion, older vehicles, and high fuel consumption contribute heavily to PM2.5, nitrogen oxides, and ozone pollution in major cities. Public transport infrastructure is still developing, leading to heavy reliance on private vehicles. Industrial and Energy Sector Emissions: Coal-fired power plants, manufacturing industries, and cement production contribute significantly to air pollution. Enforcement of emission regulations varies across regions. Biomass and Land Burning: Seasonal forest and peatland fires in Sumatra and Kalimantan produce massive smoke and haze events, drastically worsening air quality locally and in neighboring countries. Monitoring and Governance: While urban monitoring networks exist in Jakarta and some other cities, rural and forested areas are under-monitored. Coordinating between national, provincial, and municipal authorities presents challenges. Public Awareness: Awareness of health impacts from air pollution is growing, but behavior change is limited, especially in rural areas reliant on biomass and open burning.",
