            h4: "Allies: ASEAN countries facing similar urban and transboundary haze issues, including Malaysia, Singapore, and Thailand. UNEP, WHO, and UNDP for technical assistance, monitoring, and policy guidance. Developing nations advocating for equitable access to funding and technology for pollution control. Rivals / Constraints: Industrial and agricultural sectors resistant to stricter emission regulations. Neighboring countries sometimes pressuring Indonesia to address transboundary haze more aggressively.",
            h5: "Jakarta frequently experiences PM2.5 levels exceeding WHO guidelines, especially during peak traffic periods and industrial activity spikes. Seasonal peatland and forest fires contribute to extremely high PM2.5 and haze events across Sumatra, Kalimantan, and Southeast Asia. Vehicle emissions, industrial emissions, and land burning are primary contributors to urban and regional air pollution. Air pollution contributes to respiratory, cardiovascular, and other chronic diseases, leading to significant public health impacts.",
            h6: "National Legal Framework: Law No. 32/2009 on Environmental Protection and Management establishes air quality standards, emission limits, and monitoring requirements. Regulations govern industrial emissions, vehicle standards, and mandatory environmental impact assessments. Urban air quality management plans aim to reduce traffic, industrial, and biomass-related pollution. International Agreements & Obligations: Participation in UNEP global air quality initiatives and reporting frameworks. Alignment with Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) targeting reduction of mortality and disease from air pollution. Regional cooperation through ASEAN agreements to mitigate transboundary haze and pollution. Engagement with global climate initiatives linking air quality improvements to greenhouse gas reductions."
